#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:6
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:9
msgid ""
"This RFC is an amendment to [RFC 3085](https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/3085-"
"edition-2021.html) to declare that the Rust Project intends to produce a new "
"edition in 2024, to set up a [project group](https://rust-lang.github.io/"
"rfcs/2856-project-groups.html) to deliver the edition, and to establish a "
"tentative cadence for future editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:16
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:19
msgid ""
"So far, editions have been delivered on a three-year cadence, with the 2015, "
"2018, and 2021 editions. Many within the Rust project have been expecting "
"this trend to continue. The three-year cadence seems to hit a reasonable "
"balance of not too often, but still providing opportunities for potentially "
"breaking changes to be introduced."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:23
msgid ""
"By establishing a three-year cadence, this removes the ambiguity of what the "
"expectations are around scheduling and releases of new editions."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:25
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:28
msgid "2024 Edition"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:30
msgid ""
"The Rust Project intends to create a 2024 Edition. Currently, no specific "
"changes are being announced in this RFC for this edition. Teams will be "
"responsible for identifying changes they want to make and coordinate with "
"the Edition project group."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:34
msgid "Edition project group"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:36
msgid ""
"The Leadership Council will be responsible for forming a project group for "
"coordinating each edition release. The Edition project group is responsible "
"for:"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:39
msgid ""
"Ensuring that the process follows the accepted policy, such as [RFC 3085]"
"(https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/3085-edition-2021.html) and this RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:40
msgid ""
"Establishing a schedule for the edition ([example](https://hackmd.io/@m-ou-"
"se/Byh6x1thv))."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:41
msgid ""
"Building consensus within the Edition project group on which changes will be "
"accepted for the edition in coordination with the affected teams."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:42
msgid ""
"Coordinating with teams to ensure that edition changes are on track for "
"release."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:43
msgid ""
"Making recommendations to the Leadership Council if the edition should be "
"released in another year."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:44
msgid ""
"Making public announcements, such as blog posts to solicit support in "
"creating the edition, calls for testing if needed, and informing users about "
"the changes planned."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:45
msgid ""
"Ensuring that the requisite changes in tooling for changes are available in "
"the nightly release, such as adding unstable edition flags."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:46
msgid ""
"Informing the relevant people to be aware of any issues related to the "
"edition and tracking for getting those issues resolved."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:47
msgid ""
"Ensuring that sufficient testing, such as crater runs, gets done in time to "
"be evaluated and for issues to be resolved."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:48
msgid ""
"Ensuring that automated migrations are in place, and should cover the "
"majority of users."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:49
msgid ""
"Ensuring documentation, such as the [Edition Guide](https://doc.rust-lang."
"org/edition-guide/index.html), is updated, ideally in time for users to "
"begin testing before the release."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:50
msgid "Ensuring that the stabilization process happens on schedule."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:51
msgid ""
"Monitoring adoption of the edition after the stabilization, and identifying "
"issues that may need to be addressed after the release."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:52
msgid ""
"Continue to evaluate if the three year cadence makes sense, and potentially "
"make recommendations to the Leadership Council for changes to the edition "
"process."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:54
msgid ""
"The Edition project group may approve minor changes to the process outlined "
"above without public comment."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:56
msgid ""
"Major changes to the edition process, such as discarding the three-year "
"model, must be made via the RFC process."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:58
msgid ""
"The Edition project group will be part of the [launching pad](https://forge."
"rust-lang.org/governance/council.html#the-launching-pad-top-level-team), "
"though that may change in the future if the Leadership Council decides to "
"reorganize how teams and groups are organized."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:64
msgid "Edition cadence"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:66
msgid "Editions are intended to be released on a three-year cadence."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:68
msgid ""
"The Leadership Council is responsible for deciding what to do if an edition "
"does not have sufficient changes ready to justify the edition. Some possible "
"options include skipping the edition completely (and keeping the regular 3 "
"year cadence), delaying to a subsequent year, or stabilizing the edition "
"without any specific changes. It is not expected for this to happen in 2024, "
"or even 2027, and thus trying to predict the circumstances in 9+ years is "
"out of scope for this RFC."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:72
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:75
msgid "Cadence may artificially delay changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:77
msgid ""
"Some changes may be ready within the first or second year after an edition "
"is released. Or, a change may just barely miss an edition window if last-"
"minute issues arise. Forcing those changes to wait one to three more years "
"before they can be used can be a frustrating experience."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:81
msgid ""
"A more frequent cadence may allow those changes to be available in a more "
"timely manner, and potentially reduce the stress associated with the release "
"process. It is intended for the Edition project group and the Leadership "
"Council to continue to evaluate the cadence and to decide if a different "
"approach is preferred in the future."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:84
msgid "Stress around deadlines"
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:86
msgid ""
"Preparing and releasing edition changes, with such a rare window for "
"release, can be a stressful process. Changes often taken longer than "
"expected, and since most people are offering their effort as a volunteer, it "
"can be difficult to get everything ready in time. Additionally, there are "
"many time-consuming manual steps in the release process, and the Edition "
"project group has to coordinate with many different teams, which can be "
"exhausting."
msgstr ""

#: src/3501-edition-2024.md:90
msgid ""
"It is recommended that the Edition project group establish a schedule that "
"gives plenty of lead time, very publicly share the schedule, and to "
"recognize the risk of excessive stress throughout the process and to try to "
"identify strategies to mitigate it. The Edition project group should also be "
"prepared and willing to discuss options with the Leadership Council of "
"releasing in a different year if the schedule is at risk."
msgstr ""
